abstract: His pitch in Iowa couldn’t be simpler. Is it what voters want?
snippet: His pitch in Iowa couldn’t be simpler. Is it what voters want?
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — I’ve heard Joe Biden speak twice in Iowa over recent days. Both times, I walked away barely able to remember a single issue he mentioned. I had to check my notes. Ah, yes, guns: He touched on that. Climate change, too. That flitted by.

headline_main: Democrats Had a 2020 Vision. This Isn’t Quite What They Expected.
headline_print_headline: Democrats Pitched a Huge Tent In Iowa, and It’s a Hive of Angst

abstract: The Democrats in Iowa are making a furious last-minute case against the president. So is a Tea Party hero.
snippet: The Democrats in Iowa are making a furious last-minute case against the president. So is a Tea Party hero.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — The line outside the Trump rally on Thursday night was perhaps not the safest space to try to conduct a Socratic dialogue about the nature of truth. But Joe Walsh — former Tea Party congressman, former right-wing radio host, current Trump opponent — leaned right in.

abstract: Bernie Sanders is increasingly seen as the candidate on the rise. But the Iowa contest is unusually jumbled, and several candidates have realistic hopes for a sudden burst of momentum.
snippet: Bernie Sanders is increasingly seen as the candidate on the rise. But the Iowa contest is unusually jumbled, and several candidates have realistic hopes for a sudden burst of momentum.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — The Democratic presidential candidates pleaded with voters in Iowa for their last-minute consideration on Sunday, competing with the Super Bowl for caucusgoers’ attention and straining against an atmosphere of unusual uncertainty and indecision among Democrats ahead of the first-in-the-nation nominating contest.

headline_main: Coronavirus, Brexit, Australian Open: Your Monday Briefing

abstract: Caucusgoers, uniquely, will declare their loyalty before their friends and neighbors. And they are taking their responsibility very seriously.
snippet: Caucusgoers, uniquely, will declare their loyalty before their friends and neighbors. And they are taking their responsibility very seriously.
lead_paragraph: CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa — It is a public display of civic duty unique in American politics: Iowans on Monday night will stand in front of their neighbors and express their preference for a candidate for president. No curtains covering a voting machine. No private paper ballots. Just a declaration of loyalty before fellow Democrats.

headline_main: Stand Here for Your Candidate: Iowans State Their Preferences in Public
headline_print_headline: No Curtains to Hide Preferences, and Rifts

abstract: Iowa voted strongly for Barack Obama twice and for Donald Trump by nine points in 2016. It could be a national barometer again in November.
snippet: Iowa voted strongly for Barack Obama twice and for Donald Trump by nine points in 2016. It could be a national barometer again in November.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — For a full year, Democrats owned the Iowa spotlight as presidential candidates logged thousands of visits, spent tens of millions on TV and digital ads, and boasted of rallies that drew, on some of their best days, 1,000 ardent supporters hoping to defeat President Trump.
